snippet.textDisplay: This is absurd. Probability doesn't mean that BOTH things happen. It means that there is the POTENTIAL for both things to happen. Super-position doesn't mean that there are "two electrons" passing through the two-slit experiment at the same time. It means that each electron, at its core, is a wave, and the act of measuring it means we can only take a snapshot of the wave in a moment of time. That snapshot is what we call "an electron". It would be like saying that a ball has both potential and kinetic energy, depending on when you take a snapshot of the ball. That doesn't mean that there are two different balls, one with potential and one with kinetic. Looking at it that way is nonsense. And of course, it's not what the math shows. It's just how people have interpreted it.

snippet.textDisplay: If 5000 atoms decay in my body every second, then the number of parallel universes created is 2^5000. That's a number with at least 1500 zeroes on the end. And that's only from one person, in one very short time. There will be a lot of seconds in the history of the multiverse and a lot of radioactive atoms for this to happen to. And keep in mind that every single decay event does not simply add to the number of universes - it multiplies them.

snippet.textDisplay: I was probably 12 years old when I shared this thought with a friend in a soccer playground; How come when I go to sleep and then wake up, it feels no time has passed, it felt almost instantaneous (that itself must have been the measure of the quality of the sleep a teenager gets when playing endless hours under the African sun).   Then I told him how will someone know he/she is dead?  My friend responded, well people are there to bury you!  I responded frustratingly, BUT HOW DO YOU KNOW YOURSELF?! He said you are not making sense and dismissed my inquiry with equal frustration, but the thought never left me; death is relative, you are never truly dead from your perspective, but rather repeating the same cycle in many different forms as long as the laws of physics, whichever spawns your  existence, allows.  The older I got, the more I read on the latest research, the more it aligns with that gut intuition I had long long time ago.

So I guess the question is: why this Universe (or outcome) and not other? Could there be other possibilities (the way how waves in matter interact with one another) instead of the binary functions of "The Cat is dead or Alive" outcome? As this argument postulates that "The 🐈 is dead and Alive" at the same time which is an outright contradiction.
If reality branches off at given points in time, and only realizes itself when we become concious of the multiplicity of ways it could have played out: why do we think that this reality is the only outcome it could have been?
The Entanglement Theory has as its premise that: everything (matter or energy) in this Universe is interrelated (or connected with eachother), and that only a stronger force (force majeure) can "influence" the behaviour or (state) of another particle (classical physics, conditional probability, and the laws of cause and effect) which makes this universe deterministic.

snippet.textDisplay:
Different view on entanglement (but ultimately comes down to the same thing)

Picture two electrons colliding. These two electrons will change each others assets: momentum, position etc. But we don't know exactly what the values are of these assets. We do know how collision works mathematically. (Keep this in mind for later). But if we observe one electron. Because electrons are probabilistic the values of these assets get chosen randomly.
But because this electron had an effect on the other electron's assets. The calculation of the collision must "add up" giving the other electrons the value of his assets needed.

We could go further saying entanglement = The result of the assymmetry: That collision itself is determenistic (not probabilistic if you know all the variables needed). But the assets of an electron aren't.

snippet.textDisplay: The only way to show that superposition is real is to observe both (or ALL) of the superposed states.  And your reasoning asserts that it is not possible to observe more than a single state.  So, all that you have shown is that we encounter an endless string of time/space states for which we have inadequate information to predict which of multiple possible subsequent states will succeed the current state.  That is not the same thing as having shown that all possible states will come to exist.  It is a very fine grained version of the fact that you will never roll a 3½ with a six sided die.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm not sure if I understand how we actually get to the conclusion.


If everything is a quantum system, stuff is constantly decohering, and "measurement" really just means thinning down the indeterminacy to something we essentially consider a 100% definitive state.
But how does any of that predicate or necessitate a parallel world? Why couldn't it just remain within a realm of indeterminacy?


Specifically, if the radioactive particle already decohered with its environment to the point where its essentially assured in which state it is, say, not decayed. Then the cat simply doesn't die, and we observe that it didn't because the system decohered to the point where that's essentially the determined result.
How do parallel worlds come into this? Why are they needed or what reason do we have to assume their existence?


And the explanations for energy conservation seem confusing; what does it mean for the universe to be "subdivided"? Or what does the professor guy mean by internal state?

The many worlds - more exactly infinite worlds - interpretation's main issue is the fact that its either just methaphysical babbling, or it has serious issues with fermi's paradox.
Which is a good sanity check.
Similarly to how "did the number of people having cancer skyrocket?" is a good sanity check, when it comes to stuff like the Pusztai Affair, or Non-ionizing radiation (from stuff like mobile phones) causing cancer. Similarly how the "do pilots get plagued with cancer compared to the general population?" is a good sanity check for the linear no treshhold model of radiation.
Checking your theory - AND ITS IMPLICATIONS - against reality is necessity to not defraud yourself in the intellectual sense.

snippet.textDisplay: This is far from a cohesive look at quantum mechanics. While I appreciate that actual maths are being discussed, and some myths dispelled, Everett's interpretation is nothing close to the last word when it comes to quantum mechanics. I wish you had discussed more of the complex history behind the field. There is a STILL OPEN DEBATE about the nature of our universe! Making an entire video about Everett's interpretation (and seeking the opinion of someone who has a bias toward Everett's view) really does a disservice to such an exciting topic, in my opinion. The book "What Is Real?" by Adam Becker gives a much more historically based viewpoint of this discussion. He of course advocates for his own thoughts, but at least he addresses the various schools of thought on these equations and how they can be interpreted. I wish you had talked about how Bohr and his camp in Copenhagen clashed with Einstein and Schrodinger at Solvay in 1927, or the contributions of Bell and Feynman to this discussion. I think it's naive to stop at Everett and say "oh, we solved it, there's probably a bunch of other worlds out there somewhere."
